            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Kowalski is a product of two distinct San Franciscos. Born to a Polish-American longshoreman father and a Mexican-American mother from a large Mission District family, his childhood in the foggy Outer Richmond was a blend of pierogi, pozole, and the salty Pacific air. He grew up feeling like a quiet observer, navigating the loving but separate cultural worlds his parents inhabited. This instilled in him a knack for watching, listening, and understanding the mechanics behind the scenes.\n\nHis fascination with the technical side of storytelling led him to City College's Media Production program. He thrived with the hands-on equipment, more interested in coaxial cables and mixing boards than theoretical papers. His educational journey was cut short when his father suffered a debilitating back injury, forcing him out of work. At 21, Mateo took an entry-level job at a local TV station to help support his family. He traded a diploma for a union card and steady pay, a pragmatic decision that defined his career. He never regretted it, finding his true education in the hum of live broadcasting.\n\nNow 48, Mateo is a senior broadcast technician, an unseen anchor ensuring the city\u2019s news and information flows smoothly. His days are structured and precise. He leaves his rent-controlled Inner Richmond apartment, grabs a coffee on Clement Street, and takes the N-Judah downtown, his commute filled with technical podcasts. At work, he is respected for his calm demeanor and deep knowledge, a veteran who has navigated the industry\u2019s chaotic transition from analog to digital.\n\nHis social life is small but solid, centered around a weekly trivia night with a few fellow industry lifers. A decade-long relationship ended five years ago, leaving him more self-reliant and introspective. He finds solace in long walks through Golden Gate Park and photographing the city\u2019s architectural details. His dream isn't fame or fortune, but to finally use his skills for himself. He hopes to create a small, personal documentary about the changing face of the Mission, a tribute to his mother\u2019s heritage and the city that shaped him\u2014a permanent record from the man who has spent his life making sure everyone else\u2019s story gets told."
